      <elementaryExchange id="899e1068-3db9-5674-b05a-34363a9410ce" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="000811-97-2" amount="4.61427605409706E-05" elementaryExchangeId="fa0c2bee-8dd9-4f8a-8489-b1f3b43de958" formula="C2H2F4">
        <name xml:lang="en">1,1,1,2-Tetrafluoroethane</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Leakage of working fluid assuming 3.77% (annual equivalent leakage rate as per the provided literature). Eunomia (2014) report an annual equivalent leakage rates for heat pumps of 3.77% (1.81−7.63% at the low and high scenario) which are calculated as the product of the leakage frequency and the leakage rate if such a leak occurs. While the IPCC/TEAP (2005) reports that industrial refrigeraiton systems show an annual average leakage rates of 7−10%; with mallest leakage rates are observed in ammonia systems because of the pungent smell. What is also assumed is 8380 h of operation per yea, to consider maintenance, to adjust the annual leak to an hourly leak.

References:
Eunomia report for the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC). "Impacts of Leakage from Refrigerants in Heat Pumps." (2014)
IPCC/TEAP Special Report. "Safeguard of the ozone layer and the global climate system" (2005)</comment>
